    "summary": "The proto-domestication of the donkey (Equus asinus) began in northeastern Africa, particularly in the region of modern Sudan and Ethiopia, around 7000–6000 BCE. Wild African wild asses (Equus africanus) were the ancestors of the domestic donkey, and early interactions between humans and these animals appear to have begun in the context of hunting before gradually shifting toward herding and eventually controlled breeding.\n\nDonkeys were among the first pack animals used in long-distance transport and were critical to the development of overland trade across arid regions. Their ability to carry heavy loads over rough terrain and their tolerance for hot, dry conditions made them invaluable for connecting early agricultural communities across northeastern Africa and the Levant in subsequent millennia.",
